No. Rifling is already only possible because of the sort of highly accurate measuring tools that makes having calibers measured in fractions of millimeters possible. So to make it possible you're already talking about a world that is of a comparable level of technology as the 19th century, but never discovered gunpowder or anything like it. Rifling also works for softer projectiles because the tight fit actually makes the projectile engage with the rifling. And I don't think a crossbow even has the muzzle velocity (as it were) to make this possible even if these conditions could be met. And then there's the effort it would take versus normal fletching, which I estimate to be considerable.

So no, wouldn't work, wouldn't be practical. Over time a lot of people have come up with stuff like this, and 99% of the time that's the answer. The only thing I can name from the top of my head that isn't historical, but would have been historically possible, and would have presented a significant benefit over historical gear, is Joerg Sprave's Instant Legolas, judging purely from the looks of it.

As others have addressed the impact of rifling on accuracy, I'll mention that the fact that it would need to engage with the barrel for that rifling to impart stability would also tank your velocity by means of increased friction. The only reason barrel length can have a net positive impact on traditional firearm projectile velocity is by allowing the gunpowder more time to fully burn while the bullet is still riding the explosion, as the expansion of gasses happens in three-dimensional space and is channeled by the surrounding barrel. This wouldn't work with the bowstring, as it is acting in a two-dimensional plane
